 authorization2star  aContemporary anthropology is done in a world where social and digital media are playing an increasingly significant role, where anthropological and arts practices are often intertwined in museum and public intervention contexts, and where anthropologists are encouraged to engage with mass media. Because anthropologists are often expected and inspired to ensure their work engages with public issues, these opportunities to disseminate work in new ways and to new publics simultaneously create challenges as anthropologists move their practice into unfamiliar collaborative domains and expose their research to new forms of scrutiny. In this volume, contributors question whether a fresh public anthropology is emerging through these new practices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aApplied anthropologyxMethodology. 0aApplied anthropologyxPhilosophy. 0aMass media and anthropology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aApplied Anthropology, Media Studies.1 aAbram, Simone, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAbram, Simone, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBarone, Francine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBullen, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollins, Samuel Gerald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurington, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFavero, Paolo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedman, Kerim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGolub, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHart, Keith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHervik